Great question — this is a classic gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, a new DI scope is automatically created for every HTTP request, so `AddScoped<MyDbContext>()` gives you a **fresh instance per request**.

**In MAUI, there are no automatic scopes.** The app has one long-lived scope for its entire lifetime, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` is created once and reused forever — accumulating tracked entities, stale data, and change-tracker state across navigations.

### Fixes

**Option 1 — Use `AddTransient`:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();
```
Each injection gets a new instance. Simple, but you lose the ability to share a context within a single logical operation.

**Option 2 — Use `IServiceScopeFactory` to create manual scopes:**
```csharp
public class MyViewModel
{
    private readonly IServiceScopeFactory _scopeFactory;

    public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)
        => _scopeFactory = scopeFactory;

    public async Task LoadDataAsync()
    {
        using var scope = _scopeFactory.CreateScope();
        var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
        // db is fresh and will be disposed at the end of this block
    }
}
```
This is closer to what ASP.NET Core does under the hood — you control the scope boundary explicitly.

**Option 2 is generally recommended** because it gives you a clear, bounded lifetime and proper disposal, just like a per-request scope in ASP.NET Core.
